1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAKE VARIOUS CHANGES TO THE PROCESS FOR 401 WATER QUALITY
3 CERTIFICATIONS ISSUED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL
4 QUALITY, TO REFORM PERMITTING RELATED TO UPLAND BASIN MARINAS,
5 AND TO CLARIFY THAT CERTAIN MAN-MADE DITCHES ARE NOT COVERED
6 UNDER THE COASTAL AREA MANAGEMENT ACT.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 143-214.1A reads as rewritten:
9 "§ 143-214.1A. Water quality certification requirements for certain projects.
10 (a) The following requirements shall govern applications for certification filed with the
11 Department pursuant to section 401 of the Clean Water Act, 33 U.S.C. § 1341(a)(1), for (i)
12 maintenance dredging projects partially funded by the Shallow Draft Navigation Channel
13 Dredging and Aquatic Weed Fund and Fund, (ii) projects involving the distribution or
14 transmission of energy or fuel, including natural gas, diesel, petroleum, or electricity:electricity,
15 and (iii) projects involving construction of an upland basin marina, as defined in
16 G.S. 113A-129.11:
17 …
18 (c) For projects that are eligible for a Nationwide Permit or Regional General Permit
19 issued by the United States Army Corps of Engineers, which are not subject to subsection (a) of
20 this section, and are required or elect to be covered under an Individual Water Quality
21 Certification, the Department shall perform a review of an application pursuant to all of the
22 following requirements:
23 (1) On receipt of such application, the Department shall notify the applicant of
24 any required fee within five business days. If the Department does not send
25 the applicant a fee request within five business days of receipt of an
26 application, the fee is waived. The Department's review period shall begin on
27 the date the application fee is paid or on the sixth business day from receipt
28 when the application fee has been waived pursuant to this subdivision. For
29 application fees that are paid via interagency batch payment, the review period
30 shall start on receipt of the application by the Division of Water Resources.
31 The Department shall additionally post any public notice required under the
32 federal Clean Water Act within five business days of receipt of an application.
33 (2) Within 30 business days of the beginning of the review period, the Department
34 shall (i) determine whether or not the application is complete and notify the
35 applicant accordingly and, (ii) if the Department determines an application is
*S472-v-3*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 incomplete, specify all such deficiencies in a notice to the applicant. The
2 applicant may file an amended application or supplemental information to
3 cure the deficiencies identified by the Department for the Department's
4 review. Review of amended applications or supplemental information
5 responses provided by the applicant shall occur within 20 business days of
6 receipt. An application may be deemed incomplete only if it does not provide
7 sufficient information necessary for the Department to determine if the
8 proposed discharges into navigable waters will comply with State water
9 quality requirements. If the Department fails to issue a notice that the
10 application is incomplete within the requisite initial 30-day period, or the
11 supplemental 20-day review period, the application shall be deemed complete.
12 As used in this section, "State water quality requirements" means water quality
13 standards approved by the United States Environmental Protection Agency
14 pursuant to 33 U.S.C. § 1313(c)(3).
15 (3) If the Department determines that a public hearing is necessary pursuant to
16 applicable requirements, the Department shall notify the applicant within the
17 review period outlined in subdivision (2) of this subsection. If the hearing
18 officer determines that additional information is required from the applicant
19 at the conclusion of the public hearing comment period, the Department shall
20 notify the applicant within five business days of the conclusion of the
21 comment period and the supplemental information shall be subject to the
22 review time lines laid out in subdivision (2) of this subsection.
23 (4) The Department shall either approve or deny an application within (i) 10
24 business days of the date the application is deemed complete if no public
25 hearing is held or (ii) 15 business days of the close of the record if a public
26 hearing is held and no additional information is required. Failure of the
27 Department to approve or deny the application within the requisite time
28 period, as applicable, shall result in a waiver of the certification requirement
29 by the State, unless the applicant agrees, in writing, to an extension of time,
30 which shall not exceed one year from the State's receipt of the application for
31 certification.
32 (5) The Department shall issue a certification, with or without conditions or
33 limitations, upon determining that the proposed discharges into navigable
34 waters subject to the federal Clean Water Act will comply with State water
35 quality requirements. The Department may include as conditions or
36 limitations in a certification any effluent limitations or other limitations
37 necessary to assure the proposed discharges into navigable waters subject to
38 the federal Clean Water Act will comply with State water quality
39 requirements. The Department shall not impose any other conditions or
40 limitations in a certification.
41 (6) The Department shall deny a certification application only if it determines that
42 no reasonable conditions or limitations would provide assurance that the
43 proposed discharges into navigable waters subject to the federal Clean Water
44 Act will comply with State water quality requirements. The denial shall
45 include a statement explaining why the Department determined the proposed
46 discharges into navigable waters subject to the federal Clean Water Act will
47 not comply with the State water quality requirements.
48 (7) The Department may grant, deny, or waive certification but shall not require
49 an applicant to withdraw an application.
50 (d) On receipt of any application for certification filed with the Department pursuant to
51 section 401 of the Clean Water Act, 33 U.S.C. § 1341(a)(1), the Department shall notify the
